        "heading": "The Meme Stock Era: A Crash Course in Market Reality",
        "content": "<p>Early 2021 marked a unique moment in market history. Stocks like GameStop and AMC became household names not because of their fundamentals, but because of coordinated buying on social media platforms. Young investors, many using commission-free trading apps, jumped in.</p><p>For Gen Z, this was often their introduction to investing. The experience was intense: some saw portfolios double or triple in days, only to watch those gains evaporate just as quickly. The volatility taught hard lessons about the difference between speculation and investing.</p><p>The appeal was understandable. Traditional financial advice often feels inaccessible to younger people facing student debt, rising housing costs, and uncertain job markets. Meme stocks offered the allure of a shortcut. But shortcuts in investing rarely work out as planned.</p>"
