        "heading": "The Role of Financial Education in Shaping Better Investors",
        "content": "<p>One factor contributing to this generational shift is improved financial education. According to CNBC reporting, finance education in high school has helped shape how young investors approach the market.</p><p>Financial literacy programs in schools have expanded in recent years. These courses cover basics like budgeting and saving, but increasingly include investment concepts: how the stock market works, the power of compound interest, the difference between stocks and bonds, and the importance of diversification.</p><p>When young people learn these concepts before they have money to invest, they're better equipped to make rational decisions when they do. They're less likely to chase hype and more likely to build portfolios aligned with their goals and risk tolerance.</p><p>This doesn't mean every Gen Z investor who took a high school finance class avoided meme stock speculation. But education creates a foundation. When the excitement fades and losses mount, investors with financial literacy have frameworks for understanding what went wrong and how to improve.</p><p>For those who didn't receive formal financial education, resources are more accessible than ever. Online courses, podcasts, books, and reputable financial websites can fill the gap. The key is seeking out information before making investment decisions, not after.</p>"
